      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is a judicial philosophy that insists on interpreting the Constitution as it was understood at the time it was written. This approach is rooted in the belief that the Constitution is a stable, fixed document that should not be subject to the whims of contemporary judges. Originalists argue that this method respects the rule of law by adhering to the text and intent of the framers, preventing judges from imposing their own values and biases. They also contend that it limits judicial activism, ensuring that changes to constitutional interpretation are made through the democratic process, not through unelected judges. Originalism is seen as a way to maintain the Constitution's legitimacy and prevent arbitrary judicial decisions.",
